		<published>2008-11-25T10:13:36+00:00</published>
		<updated>2008-11-25T10:13:36+00:00</updated>
		<id><a href="http://my-site">http://my-site</a>:5000/cms/joomla17/index.php/developerblog/10-honoursprojectblog/43-week-9-rare-talks-superbly-useful-presentation</id>
		<summary type="html">&lt;div class=&quot;feed-description&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://img296.imageshack.us/my.php?image=spritesheetheavyweaponszr6.gif">http://img296.imageshack.us/my.php?image=spritesheetheavyweaponszr6.gif</a>&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin: 5px 10px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;<a href="http://img296.imageshack.us/img296/3214/spritesheetheavyweaponszr6.th.gif">http://img296.imageshack.us/img296/3214/spritesheetheavyweaponszr6.th.gif</a>&quot; alt=&quot;Free Image Hosting at www.ImageShack.us&quot; width=&quot;119&quot; height=&quot;165&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;This week we just had the best lecture ever!&lt;br /&gt;The lecturer is one of the lead graphic programmer from RARE Games. I'm not quite sure how to spell his fullname, and it will be a bad idea to blindly type it here so I will call him Mr.D.
&lt;p&gt;Mr.D is so awesome! and since I'm so crazy about the game graphic programming, this makes his lecture is uberly useful to me, both of the honours project and personal research PoV.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Briefly, the whole lecture was about the advance full-screen effect, which most of them have already become a standard in modern game applications.&lt;br /&gt;Personally, the full-screen effcet is not a new thing to me. I did implement them quite a few times into my past works (Direct3D, GroupProject). I found his lecture's real benefits are where he strongly confirmed most of my understanding are correct. =D&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I also noted down some programming tips as following&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Offline ambient occlusion is still the best solution for most games.&lt;br /&gt;around 32-64 rays have been casted from different angles in the offline-authoring tool&lt;br /&gt;(Will ask Martin about this!)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Imposters are rendered using the key-color (like below sprite-based image) to exclude the unwanted project area. It use no-blending at all!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Imposters could be a few frames of animation, which the texture atlas technique could be used to store images in spatial-struture form (quad-tree)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Transparency is still a major problem on many effect such as fog.&lt;br /&gt;It might sounds expensive, but we could render them again after the effect has been done to make sure we had the correct destination color while blending.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Imposters should be generated with the depth-texture&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The great example for &quot;partial-glow&quot; is TRON2.0 the game&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Deferred rendering (like deferred shading?) heavily used the fullscreen buffer, and it's memory-bound&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</summary>
